 <office:body>
  <office:text>
   <office:forms form:automatic-focus="false" form:apply-design-mode="false"/>
   <text:sequence-decls>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Illustration"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Table"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Text"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Drawing"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Figure"/>
   </text:sequence-decls>
   <text:p text:style-name="P1"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T1"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T1">Welcome to </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T2">The Compleat Barks Disney Reader</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T1">. </text:span></text:span>Designed specifically for owners of the digital <text:span text:style-name="T3">Fantagraphics</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4"> Complete Carl Barks Disney Library</text:span>, this application is a tool built to help you explore the &quot;Good Duck Artist’s&quot; career in its definitive form. The project began with a simple goal: to fulfil a lifelong dream of reading the Barks canon in its original, uncut, and chronological glory. While the Fantagraphics digital volumes provided the essential source material, generic comic readers simply couldn’t offer the curated <text:span text:style-name="T5">Barks </text:span>experience <text:span text:style-name="T5">I wanted</text:span>. <text:span text:style-name="T5">So </text:span>I developed this software to bridge that gap—creating a dedicated environment that understands the history of the work itself.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P3">Central to this experience is a dedication to Barks’ original intent. I have painstakingly reversed various censorship alterations and omissions found in the <text:span text:style-name="T5">published </text:span>volumes to present the stories as they were meant to be read. This includes restored version<text:span text:style-name="T6">s</text:span> of <text:span text:style-name="T6">WDCS #34 and </text:span>&quot;Silent Night&quot;, and the inclusion of the missing page from <text:span text:style-name="T4">WDCS #74; </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T7">all </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T3">colo</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T8">u</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T3">red in the flat Fantagraphics style.</text:span> All dialogue changes have been reverted to match the original US editions, and I have restored several elements to reflect Barks&apos; original <text:span text:style-name="T6">intent</text:span>, including &quot;Harpies&quot; in <text:span text:style-name="T4">The Golden Fleecing</text:span>, the &quot;Dere&quot; dialect in <text:span text:style-name="T4">Lost in the Andes!</text:span>, and the blank eyeballs for Bombie in <text:span text:style-name="T4">Voodoo Hoodoo</text:span>. However, I recogni<text:span text:style-name="T6">s</text:span>e that every fan has their own preference; should you disagree with any of these editorial choices, they can be easily toggled off in the settings.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P4">Beyond the restoration of specific <text:span text:style-name="T5">stories and </text:span>panels, <text:span text:style-name="T5">I wanted the</text:span> reader <text:span text:style-name="T5">to help show how Barks’ stories</text:span> evol<text:span text:style-name="T5">ved</text:span>. <text:span text:style-name="T5">So y</text:span>ou can navigate the library based on Barks’ actual story submission dates, watching his style develop over his twenty-five-year career, or explore via standard series and metadata tags. <text:span text:style-name="T6">And I’ve OCRed all of the Fantagraphics volumes narration boxes and speech bubbles and turned th</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T9">ese</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T6"> into a complete Barksian word index. You can look at what words were used in which comics.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P4">The built-in reader integrates directly with your personal collection of .zip or .cbz files, intelligently cent<text:span text:style-name="T6">re</text:span>ing pages and renumbering them according to their original publication. It also remembers your position in both the table of contents and individual stories, ensuring you can always pick up exactly where you left off.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">Visually, the interface is designed as a tribute to the master himself. By utili<text:span text:style-name="T6">s</text:span>ing <text:span text:style-name="T6">favourite</text:span> panels as backgrounds throughout the application, I’<text:span text:style-name="T5">ve </text:span>tried to make this reader &quot;wall-to-wall Barks&quot;—an immersive digital home for <text:span text:style-name="T6">one </text:span>the most influential comic book artist<text:span text:style-name="T6">s</text:span> of the 20th century.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6">GLK</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6"/>
  </office:text>
 </office:body>
</office:document>